it like the way I tried to start building them was to have no instructions.

00:36:36.659 --> 00:36:40.100
And that really kind of helped

00:36:40.100 --> 00:36:43.020
communicate all of our data points or visuals a lot better.

00:36:43.419 --> 00:36:47.060
Like someone who's non-technical should be able to go into this dashboard

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:53.219
and kind of intuitively understand what it is that you're trying to analyze

00:36:53.219 --> 00:36:55.659
or, you know, the actionable items.

00:36:56.060 --> 00:37:02.340
You shouldn't need to give them training over training or a long FAQ

00:37:02.340 --> 00:37:06.020
in order for them to like come out with actionable insights.

00:37:06.260 --> 00:37:08.540
So anyway, just wanted to chime in with that.

00:37:08.979 --> 00:37:10.300
I love that.

00:37:10.300 --> 00:37:15.699
You know, I mean, what's ultimately our purpose being in analytics, right?

00:37:15.979 --> 00:37:20.820
It's it's not to produce like dashboards and give people data,

00:37:21.139 --> 00:37:23.979
but it's to make people understand what the data means.

00:37:24.419 --> 00:37:28.260
And I think there is a very definitive difference between the two,

00:37:29.699 --> 00:37:32.659
you know, which is also one of the drives

00:37:32.659 --> 00:37:36.820
why we actually went away from just churning out dashboard after dashboard,

00:37:37.340 --> 00:37:39.580
because you don't actually know

00:37:40.340 --> 00:37:44.860
how someone receives that information if they're on their own.

00:37:45.260 --> 00:37:49.379
So, you know, I think over the like the last few

00:37:51.540 --> 00:37:55.580
months, years, sort of like the concept of data

00:37:55.580 --> 00:38:00.500
translation has been like a little bit more sort of up and front center.

00:38:00.500 --> 00:38:03.860
I don't know if anyone has like heard of that, but like, you know,

00:38:03.860 --> 00:38:07.820
Google is now hiring like data translators, which, you know,

00:38:07.820 --> 00:38:10.699
feels like that's kind of what we should be doing, I guess.

00:38:11.979 --> 00:38:13.580
But like that's what it comes down to.

00:38:13.580 --> 00:38:15.979
And I think you're on the right path where,

00:38:17.020 --> 00:38:19.860
you know, if you're building a data product,

00:38:19.860 --> 00:38:22.939
I think the idea is that you have to build it in a way

00:38:23.260 --> 00:38:27.179
that it's intuitive enough for someone to use it, because if it's not,

00:38:27.620 --> 00:38:32.379
then it can become it can start feeling like work.

00:38:32.580 --> 00:38:35.979
And you don't I don't think that's the purpose of us, right?

00:38:35.979 --> 00:38:40.739
We're as as people in analytics or data science.

00:38:41.260 --> 00:38:44.860
It's our job to, you know, give people

00:38:45.500 --> 00:38:48.260
more information and help them make decisions

00:38:48.860 --> 00:38:51.260
based off of information that we can give them,

00:38:52.379 --> 00:38:55.659
rather than kind of like adding another thing onto like that plate

00:38:55.780 --> 00:38:57.979
that they have to check every day.

00:38:57.979 --> 00:39:00.860
So I love that you went through those iterations and,

00:39:01.459 --> 00:39:04.780
you know, kind of like thought through like what was working and what wasn't.

00:39:04.860 --> 00:39:06.620
That's that's great.

00:39:09.100 --> 00:39:11.540
Mike, I see you have a hand raised.

00:39:11.540 --> 00:39:16.179
Yeah, sorry if I'm off beam here, but isn't this essentially a kind of agile

00:39:16.179 --> 00:39:19.379
approach, you know, because if you

00:39:20.139 --> 00:39:23.939
if you listen to what they want, right, and then you're interpreting

00:39:24.340 --> 00:39:28.500
what they're asking for in terms of what you can actually deliver to them.

00:39:29.260 --> 00:39:32.899
But if you know, if if it takes you six months to get an answer,

00:39:32.899 --> 00:39:35.419
as you've just said, Mattias, they're not there.

00:39:35.419 --> 00:39:39.020
Essentially, you're not there for them in that time.

00:39:40.540 --> 00:39:43.260
But, you know, they better not wait six months to find out

00:39:43.260 --> 00:39:45.939
that they could have got the same answer through a normal regression

00:39:45.939 --> 00:39:48.020
within six minutes.

00:39:48.020 --> 00:39:52.300
So you then got to kind of go, well, how do I keep them on the hook

00:39:52.300 --> 00:39:55.939
and bring them, as you say, bring them with you, but keep delivering stuff

00:39:55.939 --> 00:40:00.379
to them that will say in the absence of my all encompassing model

00:40:00.379 --> 00:40:03.379
of absolutely everything, let me give you something just now

00:40:03.379 --> 00:40:06.860
that will help you and convince you that it's worth waiting six months.

00:40:08.219 --> 00:40:10.100
Is that fair or am I?

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:12.540
I like that idea of thinking of that way.

00:40:13.340 --> 00:40:17.419
I think ultimately it comes it comes down to the ownership idea

00:40:17.739 --> 00:40:22.260
where, you know, data products are for someone.

00:40:22.260 --> 00:40:25.179
Like we're not building data products for ourselves in mobile.

00:40:25.179 --> 00:40:29.860
We're building data products for ourselves in most cases that I guess

00:40:29.860 --> 00:40:33.899
there might be instances where, you know, like we have internal stuff running

00:40:33.899 --> 00:40:37.860
that just checks, you know, whether certain ETL processes ran correctly.

00:40:39.659 --> 00:40:42.979
But in most instances, a data product in the end,

00:40:43.459 --> 00:40:46.060
while we're the ones that know how to operate it,

00:40:46.060 --> 00:40:48.540
how to troubleshoot it if something goes wrong,

00:40:49.179 --> 00:40:51.260
how to build the next iteration off of it.

00:40:52.100 --> 00:40:56.020
They're not our dashboards or they're not our, you know, models,

00:40:56.179 --> 00:40:59.780
they're there for someone else, and I think that's where it comes down to

00:41:00.020 --> 00:41:03.219
where you need to have people feel that they own this thing

00:41:03.540 --> 00:41:05.899
rather than, oh, this is something analytics did.

00:41:05.899 --> 00:41:07.340
I don't understand it.

00:41:07.340 --> 00:41:10.060
It just does something and I use it.

00:41:11.100 --> 00:41:15.260
They you know, that's that's where I think you get the adoption idea from.

00:41:16.459 --> 00:41:19.780
And yeah, I'm a proponent of the idea that,

00:41:20.139 --> 00:41:24.100
you know, you can really only build a product for someone

00:41:25.500 --> 00:41:28.419
if you involve them in the process of when it's being built.

00:41:29.340 --> 00:41:30.659
So, yeah, I agree with that.

00:41:30.659 --> 00:41:34.939
We kind of use a sort of faux agile methodology internally

00:41:35.659 --> 00:41:38.939
because the marketing our marketing team isn't on like

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:42.820
we have a project, a product project management tool,

00:41:44.500 --> 00:41:46.139
but it's not on the technical side.

00:41:46.139 --> 00:41:48.340
So like it's not like we use Jira or anything

00:41:48.340 --> 00:41:51.300
where we could do a true sprinting process,

00:41:51.300 --> 00:41:53.060
which, again, is kind of like

00:41:53.060 --> 00:41:55.899
us trying to adapt into the marketing organization

00:41:55.899 --> 00:41:58.820
and trying to use what they're using, even though, you know,

00:41:58.820 --> 00:42:01.739
it's it's not the perfect solution for us.

00:42:02.500 --> 00:42:04.780
But I think that's where it comes down to.

00:42:04.780 --> 00:42:08.620
We try to be as helpful to the rest of the organization as we can be.

00:42:09.139 --> 00:42:11.260
Whatever that might mean.

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:14.139
Yeah. A wise old statistician once said to me,

00:42:14.139 --> 00:42:16.699
people are going to make decisions whether you're ready or not.

00:42:18.860 --> 00:42:22.340
You know, so so you'd best have something that will at least influence them

00:42:22.340 --> 00:42:24.260
in kind of the right direction.

00:42:24.260 --> 00:42:27.739
And as I say, like being able to at least say it's worth waiting

00:42:27.739 --> 00:42:30.979
because, you know, we can give you something good now, but by golly,

00:42:30.979 --> 00:42:34.580
by the time you really got to the bottom of this, it'll be worth waiting for.

00:42:35.340 --> 00:42:38.300
I love that. Yeah, I subscribe to that.

00:42:39.979 --> 00:42:42.739
In the spirit of remaining true to the format,

00:42:42.739 --> 00:42:46.939
Zach, is the next question I have time stamped around outlier detection.

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:54.540
Yeah, so for me, like I find it quite interesting looking at outliers

00:42:54.820 --> 00:42:58.179
becoming patterns, especially as you get more and more data.

00:42:59.419 --> 00:43:04.139
Of course, I'm guessing for you, Matthias, you have already loads of data.

00:43:04.139 --> 00:43:08.780
So it's not like you're getting lots of data, but patterns do emerge outliers.

00:43:08.780 --> 00:43:10.820
You I don't know.

00:43:12.699 --> 00:43:16.300
My general idea at the moment is if it happens once and it's an outlier,

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:20.739
if it happens twice and I research a bit more and it happens a third time,

00:43:21.179 --> 00:43:24.020
then I go, actually, this isn't an outlier.

00:43:24.020 --> 00:43:26.500
This is becoming an emerging pattern.

00:43:26.500 --> 00:43:30.139
Of course, like scales one, two and three depend on how big your data you're looking at.

00:43:30.820 --> 00:43:35.659
I was wondering how you do that with the size of data that you have.

00:43:35.659 --> 00:43:37.939
I'm assuming it's all automated.

00:43:37.939 --> 00:43:41.419
It is incredibly interesting to talk about this question,

00:43:41.419 --> 00:43:44.260
because if you had asked me,

00:43:44.260 --> 00:43:49.179
you know, I think I've been with CM now for like roughly three and a half, four years or so.

00:43:49.500 --> 00:43:54.020
If you'd asked me before my time here, I would have given you a completely different answer,

00:43:54.659 --> 00:44:00.300
because I think from a data perspective, the first thing that you generally do,

00:44:00.300 --> 00:44:04.820
you know, like the first thing that they teach you is, well, just,

00:44:04.939 --> 00:44:07.540
you know, the outliers probably should be normalized out.

00:44:07.540 --> 00:44:11.780
Or, you know, like if you build a model like, you know, like you kind of have to make sure

00:44:11.780 --> 00:44:13.739
that it's not affected by outliers.

00:44:15.219 --> 00:44:19.300
I've actually completely like changed my thinking on that working here,

00:44:19.780 --> 00:44:27.500
because some of the products that we have are like the outliers are the things that matter.

00:44:27.699 --> 00:44:32.540
Like the specifically for a brand like Sailthru, for example,

00:44:32.780 --> 00:44:39.139
which is sort of on our enterprise and, you know, the marketing there is on the ABM side.

00:44:39.179 --> 00:44:40.139
So what does this mean?

00:44:40.459 --> 00:44:45.300
It's not a volume business, but it's, you know, very much,

00:44:45.300 --> 00:44:49.100
we essentially already kind of know the opportunities,

00:44:49.100 --> 00:44:53.780
the accounts that we'd like to target, and we target that way.

00:44:53.780 --> 00:45:03.500
And, you know, it really makes a big difference if a singular account like closes or don't, or doesn't.

00:45:03.899 --> 00:45:10.620
And, you know, from that perspective, I've changed my stance on outliers,

00:45:10.620 --> 00:45:16.419
because it feels like for some brands, those are the things that are actually interesting.

00:45:16.780 --> 00:45:21.939
And when it comes to outlier detection, that is something that you have to keep in mind

00:45:21.939 --> 00:45:29.300
that is it for something where it can be like a something that you're actually looking for?

00:45:29.300 --> 00:45:33.060
Or is it something that you're trying to figure out how do I build a good model

00:45:33.060 --> 00:45:36.139
so, you know, it still is statistically valid.

00:45:37.820 --> 00:45:42.179
There is a lot of, I forget who said the whole of this is startupy.

00:45:42.540 --> 00:45:49.699
But like, there is a lot of startups now that deal with this type of issue as well.

00:45:49.939 --> 00:45:52.500
Like one big one is like outlier AI.

00:45:52.500 --> 00:45:54.260
I don't know if anyone's heard of them.

00:45:54.500 --> 00:46:00.179
But they do similar processes where you essentially just push all the data that you have to them

00:46:00.179 --> 00:46:04.500
and they build models for you on the outlier detection.

00:46:06.020 --> 00:46:08.659
I felt like I want to be the owner of that.

00:46:08.659 --> 00:46:16.179
So we do, we write all this internally, because of this reason that I don't want someone else

00:46:16.179 --> 00:46:20.260
to make the decision of this specific outlier.

00:46:20.419 --> 00:46:25.020
Is this just, is it a true outlier that, you know, a couple years ago, I'd be like,

00:46:25.020 --> 00:46:26.540
okay, let me just ignore this.

00:46:26.899 --> 00:46:29.939
Or is this something that we actually should look into further,

00:46:30.260 --> 00:46:32.379
because there's a business opportunity here.

00:46:32.580 --> 00:46:36.419
And in many cases, we found that that is actually what's happening.

00:46:36.699 --> 00:46:39.260
So, yeah, outliers are a finicky thing.

00:46:39.260 --> 00:46:43.899
And I feel like I kind of go back and forth between, like, what I think of them, you know,

00:46:44.379 --> 00:46:48.860
depending on what type of project I'm working on, whether, you know, I love them one day,

00:46:48.899 --> 00:46:52.620
and then, you know, I hate them on the next because they mess everything up.

00:46:56.620 --> 00:46:57.419
Okay, thank you.

00:46:57.419 --> 00:47:01.340
Santiago, Santiago has a great question that he put into the chat.

00:47:01.699 --> 00:47:02.459
All of them are great.

00:47:02.459 --> 00:47:05.820
I have to say that, but I particularly like Santiago's.

00:47:05.820 --> 00:47:07.500
Are you still on the line, Santiago?

00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:08.659
Would you be comfortable sharing?

00:47:09.219 --> 00:47:14.939
I am. So let's go back to kind of the previous line of thread of questions.

00:47:14.939 --> 00:47:20.500
So outside of a specific project, and educating folks on that,

00:47:20.979 --> 00:47:25.939
have you done anything successfully or failed even to try

00:47:25.939 --> 00:47:28.699
to educate the broader marketing team?

00:47:28.939 --> 00:47:35.459
For example, have considered Lunch and Learns, or like a newsletter or something?

00:47:35.459 --> 00:47:35.820
I don't know.

00:47:36.100 --> 00:47:38.300
Any thoughts?

00:47:38.300 --> 00:47:39.020
Oh, goodness.

00:47:39.020 --> 00:47:43.419
I think it's, if you figure out how to do it, it's the Holy Grail.

00:47:43.540 --> 00:47:50.739
In a sense, it is a bit about setting expectations, right?

00:47:50.739 --> 00:47:54.060
Like, what does democratizing data actually mean?

00:47:54.419 --> 00:48:01.699
And if you set out for, you know, like I said, we're, you know, a bit of 100 people

00:48:01.699 --> 00:48:06.379
in marketing, setting out with the expectation that everyone's going to be

00:48:06.379 --> 00:48:10.300
like a closet data analyst, that's not going to happen.

00:48:10.739 --> 00:48:16.659
However, what you can do is make people understand the power that data has.

00:48:16.659 --> 00:48:21.100
And the way that you do that is to give them the understanding,

00:48:21.100 --> 00:48:25.419
or have them understand how well it can help them make decisions.

00:48:25.780 --> 00:48:29.979
I think in this process, one of the things that I try to emphasize is

00:48:29.979 --> 00:48:35.580
that I'm not the decision maker on things, nor is my team.

00:48:35.580 --> 00:48:40.459
So when we do analytics, and we provide like a data product to someone,

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:45.620
it is still that someone's decision to make in the end of what they want to do.

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:51.260
I don't take that power away from my team or from the marketing organization.

00:48:51.620 --> 00:48:58.620
And I'm very protective over the fact that I feel like data should be a neutral party

00:48:58.620 --> 00:49:04.300
to someone, like a completely, essentially just giving someone,

00:49:04.540 --> 00:49:07.899
here's everything that we feel like from a data perspective,

00:49:08.300 --> 00:49:10.540
you need in order to make a decision.

00:49:10.780 --> 00:49:16.820
But then the way that you empower someone, and actually have them understand what the value

00:49:16.820 --> 00:49:22.060
of information is, is if you still let them come to their own conclusion

00:49:22.060 --> 00:49:25.219
about how this decision should be made.

00:49:25.219 --> 00:49:32.100
I think some organizations have the approach that, you know, there's like a, you know,

00:49:32.100 --> 00:49:36.300
maybe a business, a biz ops team that does all the analysis.

00:49:36.300 --> 00:49:41.419
And they, you know, push essentially their thoughts into like an organization.

00:49:41.580 --> 00:49:44.379
And then that's the thing that everyone kind of has to follow.

00:49:44.699 --> 00:49:50.899
And I think that's a really, really quick way of having people sort of not participate

00:49:50.899 --> 00:49:53.860
in this idea of, hey, data is actually important.

00:49:54.179 --> 00:50:01.620
Because you can give people data, but the only way if that people will actually start using it

00:50:01.620 --> 00:50:06.780
and that you truly democratize it, has to come from that person.

00:50:06.899 --> 00:50:10.899
It's not something that you can force someone to do.

00:50:11.179 --> 00:50:14.939
So that, I guess, is my longer answer to this.

00:50:14.939 --> 00:50:16.219
We've certainly done a lot.

00:50:16.219 --> 00:50:21.580
In fact, I, next week, I'm teaching the entire marketing organization, Looker, yet again.

00:50:21.699 --> 00:50:25.699
So I'm still doing sort of lunch and darns.

00:50:25.699 --> 00:50:28.899
Absolutely, I don't think we're all going to get around that.

00:50:29.219 --> 00:50:35.020
But yeah, the idea is people are going to, to me, people are going to adopt it

00:50:35.580 --> 00:50:42.979
if you make them understand that what they can do with it can actually make their life easier.

00:50:43.260 --> 00:50:49.500
And it can help them sort of put more behind their own job, rather than, you know,

00:50:49.500 --> 00:50:53.419
kind of mandating, hey, this is the data that you need to use.

00:50:53.780 --> 00:50:56.379
And this is the right way to do it.

00:50:56.739 --> 00:51:02.300
I think it takes a little bit more of a defined approach to make sure that people actually buy

00:51:02.300 --> 00:51:05.979
into your idea of being a data-driven organization.

00:51:08.820 --> 00:51:10.219
Cool. Yeah, that all makes sense.

