a really smart idea or smart models, but it hasn't worked.

00:52:29.179 --> 00:52:34.860
So I sense you seem to be successful in what you're doing.

00:52:34.860 --> 00:52:35.899
How do you monitor that?

00:52:35.899 --> 00:52:38.139
How do you know that you're heading in the right direction?

00:52:38.139 --> 00:52:39.580
What are the bright spots you look for?

00:52:40.139 --> 00:52:42.540
Yeah, I love that question.

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:48.780
And also, I love that idea of having a non-traditional path into analytics.

00:52:49.500 --> 00:52:52.379
My undergrad is in visual and motion design.

00:52:52.379 --> 00:52:58.060
So I definitely have a very weird path into analytics.

00:52:58.060 --> 00:53:00.300
So I'm on your side on this.

00:53:01.659 --> 00:53:09.260
To answer your actual question, though, to me, it comes back to, can you measure how

00:53:09.260 --> 00:53:10.780
successful this actually is?

00:53:11.500 --> 00:53:15.020
And how do you do this is through testing and experimentation.

00:53:15.020 --> 00:53:21.500
I think the way to prove that something is working or not working, the quickest way to

00:53:21.500 --> 00:53:28.459
do this is if you think about statistics, can we understand what would have happened

00:53:28.459 --> 00:53:29.500
if we didn't do it?

00:53:29.500 --> 00:53:37.340
Or can we understand what's changing based off of our proposed changes?

00:53:38.379 --> 00:53:42.379
Obviously, I don't know exactly what you said you're in the nonprofit space.

00:53:42.379 --> 00:53:47.419
So obviously, not entirely sure where exactly that would be applied.

00:53:47.419 --> 00:53:54.780
But from a marketing perspective, for example, we do a lot of when we propose an action.

00:53:55.340 --> 00:54:05.340
So say we find that we are running a podcast ad, or say the marketing campaign manager

00:54:05.340 --> 00:54:07.500
for a certain brand wants to buy a podcast.

00:54:07.979 --> 00:54:13.979
And we would likely suggest from an analytics perspective, then when that podcast is bought,

00:54:14.540 --> 00:54:17.500
can you buy it in certain DMAs?

00:54:17.500 --> 00:54:24.780
So DMAs are marketing regions, essentially, where then we could track, OK, what's happening

00:54:24.780 --> 00:54:30.459
between all the regions where the podcast was run versus the one where nothing happened?

00:54:31.500 --> 00:54:33.419
And then is there an actual lift in that?

00:54:34.060 --> 00:54:37.899
Obviously, that's a very sort of marketing way of thinking about it.

00:54:37.899 --> 00:54:48.780
But I would suspect that there is a lot of things that if you think about what would

00:54:48.780 --> 00:54:55.979
happen if nothing, if we didn't do anything, and you can keep a hold out of that, and then

00:54:55.979 --> 00:55:01.020
compare to what's actually happening, that would be a way to actually get definitive

00:55:01.020 --> 00:55:04.780
data on whether or not whatever you're doing is working well.

00:55:05.659 --> 00:55:06.620
Does that answer your question?

00:55:06.620 --> 00:55:09.820
Or was it more from an organizational perspective?

00:55:09.820 --> 00:55:15.739
And now as I was talking through it, are you trying to prove value for the organization?

00:55:15.739 --> 00:55:22.620
Are you trying to prove value for whatever you're actually doing?

00:55:22.620 --> 00:55:23.580
Yeah, it's interesting.

00:55:23.580 --> 00:55:24.939
I think it's the latter.

00:55:25.100 --> 00:55:31.179
I think there is the mission of the organization, what we're trying to accomplish.

00:55:31.179 --> 00:55:37.500
But then also, part of that is internal development.

00:55:40.139 --> 00:55:43.580
My most recent mandate is to help us become more data-driven.

00:55:45.580 --> 00:55:47.500
So nothing too trivial.

00:55:51.500 --> 00:55:52.379
So it's both.

00:55:52.379 --> 00:55:53.100
It's both and.

00:55:54.060 --> 00:56:01.020
You know, I have a great vision of being able or trying to help us to, like I say,

00:56:01.020 --> 00:56:01.899
accomplish our mission.

00:56:01.899 --> 00:56:08.780
But I think internally, there's this idea that we really have to shepherd the resources

00:56:08.780 --> 00:56:10.219
that we have well.

00:56:10.219 --> 00:56:13.739
And how do we do that best internally by making the best decisions?

00:56:13.739 --> 00:56:15.179
So it's decision-making in that.

00:56:15.979 --> 00:56:21.739
It's interesting because becoming data-driven is obviously very bust for me.

00:56:21.820 --> 00:56:30.060
I think if that's a definitive goal, which is fantastic, I think one of the questions

00:56:30.060 --> 00:56:35.580
I would have, if this is like one thing that, you know, look, Morris, your job this year

00:56:35.580 --> 00:56:45.419
is going to be to make us more data-driven, to go back to trying to understand what the

00:56:45.419 --> 00:56:49.020
actual idea is behind what they're trying to accomplish.

00:56:49.659 --> 00:56:57.899
I think I would have asked, you know, sort of, I'll preface this with the fact that I

00:56:57.899 --> 00:57:00.379
work in a very non-corporate environment.

00:57:01.020 --> 00:57:05.580
But if I think about like my corporate days back in like older jobs, I think one of the

00:57:05.580 --> 00:57:10.060
things that stuck with me are sort of like the idea of smart goals.

00:57:10.060 --> 00:57:15.100
So essentially, you know, can you measure your goal?

00:57:15.820 --> 00:57:18.860
And being data-driven is really hard to measure, right?

00:57:18.860 --> 00:57:25.979
So like I think if someone gave me that role or that idea or that quest, you know, how

00:57:25.979 --> 00:57:31.820
can you increase data literacy or, you know, make people more data-driven?

00:57:33.100 --> 00:57:38.379
I think I would want to know what does that actually mean to the person that's asking

00:57:38.379 --> 00:57:41.659
me what I've done.

00:57:41.659 --> 00:57:42.379
I can tell you.

00:57:42.379 --> 00:57:47.659
So weirdly, I've been in a similar boat in the past where, you know, I just mentioned

00:57:47.820 --> 00:57:49.020
Looker trainings.

00:57:49.020 --> 00:57:54.459
So this is sort of like a, you know, hit to the past for me, but somehow I'm still responsible

00:57:54.459 --> 00:57:56.060
for teaching everyone that.

00:57:57.340 --> 00:58:03.820
But what we've done in the past several years ago, one of the things that was on my sort

00:58:03.820 --> 00:58:09.820
of, you know, list of responsibilities was democratizing data across the organization,

00:58:10.379 --> 00:58:11.899
which is similarly open-ended.

00:58:12.540 --> 00:58:17.820
And the way that I tracked it and the way that I could prove it for these Looker trainings,

00:58:17.820 --> 00:58:23.739
for example, I had set out a quick survey before the Looker training, gauging everyone's

00:58:23.739 --> 00:58:31.580
understanding of what Looker is, what their level of comfort is, can they build a dashboard

00:58:31.580 --> 00:58:36.139
and manipulate a dashboard, you know, and kind of like understand where the baseline

00:58:36.139 --> 00:58:38.219
is and then did the training.

00:58:38.219 --> 00:58:43.899
And then two weeks later, essentially asked them again for a survey, which did show like

00:58:43.899 --> 00:58:48.459
pretty considerable increases in like how people felt about how they could use business

00:58:48.459 --> 00:58:49.100
intelligence.

00:58:50.219 --> 00:58:55.580
So that might be in a way for you if you have to sort of get buy-in from leadership.

00:58:56.459 --> 00:59:01.899
Those were the things I would think about, like, how can we prove that whatever we're

00:59:01.899 --> 00:59:06.620
doing, you know, has some success with it.

00:59:06.620 --> 00:59:09.820
And yeah, that's how I did it from the BI side.

00:59:11.419 --> 00:59:14.780
And yeah, there's probably opportunities like that.

00:59:15.979 --> 00:59:16.540
Yeah, thank you.

00:59:16.540 --> 00:59:17.100
That's helpful.

00:59:18.459 --> 00:59:18.959
Yeah.

