00:59:32.300 --> 00:59:34.780
your question wrong, Peter, but feel free to jump in.

00:59:35.419 --> 00:59:41.020
His question was, how do you balance steering clear of flashy new things when keeping your

00:59:41.020 --> 00:59:42.459
skills current?

00:59:42.459 --> 00:59:43.340
I don't know if I can.

00:59:45.179 --> 00:59:47.500
So it definitely is a balance.

00:59:47.500 --> 00:59:54.459
I think that's where it comes down to because I think technology is moving so fast that

00:59:54.459 --> 00:59:59.179
if you don't look for those shiny things and at least know about them and kind of have

00:59:59.179 --> 01:00:06.459
an understanding of what they do, then it can be rough, right?

01:00:07.100 --> 01:00:09.500
Because who knows what's going to be around in five years.

01:00:10.139 --> 01:00:15.500
I think one of the good examples, and I'm going to really completely butcher this, but

01:00:15.500 --> 01:00:19.820
if you think about like book printing, right, that was like, this is where I butcher it,

01:00:19.820 --> 01:00:22.139
maybe 1400, 1500 or something.

01:00:22.699 --> 01:00:27.899
And then, you know, like the actual first digital printer was like in 1990.

01:00:28.540 --> 01:00:33.100
And then all of a sudden, you know, a 3D printer was in like 2000 and whatever.

01:00:33.100 --> 01:00:38.939
So I think that is the pace of technology where, you know, you go from a very sort of

01:00:38.939 --> 01:00:45.739
study, you know, innovation to like very, becoming very exponential very, very quickly.

01:00:45.739 --> 01:00:47.899
And I think the same is true for data science.

01:00:47.899 --> 01:00:49.580
The same is true for analytics.

01:00:49.580 --> 01:00:52.060
There's so many things that are happening all the time.

01:00:52.060 --> 01:00:55.899
See, I feel like I was doing well on the 1400 to 1500.

01:00:55.899 --> 01:00:57.500
I got to pat myself on the back there.

01:00:58.860 --> 01:01:01.419
But technology is just moving super quickly.

01:01:01.419 --> 01:01:09.659
And if you don't have an aptitude to kind of like follow things and kind of be open to

01:01:09.659 --> 01:01:16.620
learning new things, then I'm not sure if analytics is going to be a great fit for you

01:01:16.620 --> 01:01:19.500
because there's just so many things you're going to have to keep up with.

01:01:21.899 --> 01:01:31.100
On the other hand, and I forget who said it, but ultimately, what we talked about earlier,

01:01:32.860 --> 01:01:40.219
you have to keep in mind that what you're making is only as good as, you know, people

01:01:40.219 --> 01:01:41.899
understanding and people utilizing it.

01:01:42.860 --> 01:01:53.020
So sometimes a more simple model that's more easily read and more adoptable outperforms

01:01:53.020 --> 01:01:54.060
the shiny thing.

01:01:55.580 --> 01:02:01.820
So I think in that sense, it's really important to think about the business requirements.

01:02:01.820 --> 01:02:09.899
So you cannot sort of let yourself make that mistake of, okay, I just really want to do

01:02:09.979 --> 01:02:15.020
natural language processing because I feel like it would be really cool if it has no

01:02:15.020 --> 01:02:16.300
application to what you're doing.

01:02:17.260 --> 01:02:24.780
So you can't let your sort of personality try to dictate what the business needs.

01:02:26.620 --> 01:02:27.739
I hope that answers it.

